note.body:
Looks like I had an older version of Fractal still (I always forget to update flatpak....)

Now that I know what we're talking about, I agree that this particular one is not a link.

I personally don't think it should be a toggle button. It's more like a Gtk menu button because it opens a popup rather than turns something on/off. Regardless, on buttons of any sort, Orca excludes them from the descendant generation if they have the has-popup state. That was inspired by the three-dot "menu button" from Tuba and the fact that I haven't yet found any Gtk list items in gnome-settings or Adwaita demo with menu buttons. I hope that will always be the case. 

Anyway, if Fractal added the has-popup state to its widget that has a popup, I believe you wouldn't hear that item.

One could also make the case that the avatar is an image that happens to have a click action. Orca excludes images from descendant generation. Again, it's looking for widgets. So if this image stopped claiming to be a button (toggle or plain), and started claiming to be an image, Orca should stop speaking that item.

note.body:
Sorry for being spammy, but I just noticed something from the report that was scrolled off screen due to how the report text was quoted. Here's that text wrapped:

> Description of the issue: The mentioned control is actionable and has functionality but is missing a button role.

So it seems like they may want a different role (i.e. the "button" role). In that case, here's my revised answer:

1. Starting with Orca v47, Orca looks inside list items for presentable descendants such as those switches and announces them as well. (Switches happen to be exposed to Orca as checkboxes, so Orca says "checkbox checked" instead of "switch on" or "button". If the auditors tested with an older version of Orca, they would not have gotten that presentation. If they were to retest with the current stable version of Orca, they should hear that presentation.
2. Changing the list item role to a button role is NOT advised.

target_title: GtkListBoxRow entries role not mentioned by the screen reader

note.body:
BTW, in case there are other bugs boiling down to "Orca doesn't speak this role," please see `_should_speak_role()` in `speech_generator.py`.

Roles should be spoken when they tell you something you might not have known, and that you potentially need to know in order to know how to interact with the widget. Given this particular case, Orca tells you when you have entered the list. Until Orca tells you otherwise, you're navigating among list items inside the list Orca just told you about. Knowing that you're in a list tells you that Up/Down Arrow is the likely means to navigate that list. Hearing "list item" each and every time doesn't tell the user anything they didn't know already.

target_title: Orca doesn't announce root in JTree

note.body:
Just a few observations based on the logs:
- In both cases (the root and the child), the selection-changed event comes *before* the descendant changed event, so the logic in the java specific toolkit script which should filter out the selection change does not apply
- The selection interface implementation of the tree looks broken - for the child focus event, it reports 0 children selected
- But, ironically, that actually saves the non-root node presentation from being silent as well, because for the child, the selection event processing updates the locus of focus to the tree itself, and then the subsequent active-descendant-changed event updates the locus of focus where it should be, and presents it
- The root would be presented as well, but only if the presentation was not interrupted in the descendant-changed event
- I assume that Orca 48 would present it, because the interruption logic is now gone

@joanmarie thanks for the quick response!

> This came up in Tor Browser development because our "onion site authentication" popup shows the password input with a red outline and an error message if the password is the wrong format or fails. I wanted to represent this semantically with `aria-invalid` and `aria-errormessage`, but Orca did not read the state.

Another thing I noticed when testing this is that `aria-errormessage` is ignored in the popup, even for `type="text"`. As far as I can tell [the code seems to require the entry is part of a document context for the error message relation to be read](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/orca/-/blob/3b30031bc756b065babc7dd904687d2204acc3ea/src/orca/scripts/web/script_utilities.py?page=4#L3501), and this popup fails this since it is part of the chrome rather than a web page. But I'm not sure why this condition is in place, could you explain it?

This isn't as important as just the "invalid" state, since the error message is still read aloud as an alert. And there's a good chance we change this in the future anyway.

note.body:
This is easy to reproduce.
1. Use either i3 or ratpoison, they both cause this.
For this example, it's enough to do this in .xinitrc:
```
#!/bin/bash
firefox https://allinaccess.com &
/usr/local/bin/orca &
exec ratpoison
```

This will start Firefox and my website should come up.

From there, make sure you're in browse mode. Press the right arrow to move by character. Almost every character spoken will re-read the window title.

The window managers that cause this seem to be the ones that don't send `WM_TAKE_FOCUS` events. I'm not familiar enough with the stack to know why this matters, though.

note.body:
**TL;DR:** If `GTK_ACCESSIBLE_ROLE_GENERIC` winds up being automatically exposed as an [Atspi `ROLE_PANEL`](https://docs.gtk.org/atspi2/enum.Role.html#panel), cool. Maybe your making that change will be all we need to solve this problem. In which case, thanks!!

<sotto voce>Let's just hope someone doesn't come along later and change the exposure of `GTK_ACCESSIBLE_ROLE_GENERIC` to `ROLE_SECTION` for all of GTK because ARIA.</sotto voce>

**Details/Explanation:** 

*IF* `GTK_ACCESSIBLE_ROLE_GENERIC` is expected to be the same thing as the [ARIA "generic" role](https://w3c.github.io/aria/#generic), and *IF* the GTK maintainers would like to adhere strictly to the ARIA expectations (i.e. CORE-AAM mappings) *THEN* technically/officially the [mapping](https://w3c.github.io/core-aam/#role-map-generic) should be to `ROLE_SECTION`; not to `ROLE_PANEL`.

*HOWEVER*, a `GtkBox` IMHO should NOT be exposed as a section.`ROLE_SECTION` is how the `div` element is exposed. [`ROLE_SECTION` is expected to contain document content](https://docs.gtk.org/atspi2/enum.Role.html#section). And the UI in question is not document content.

More relevantly, Orca doesn't treat `ROLE_SECTION` like `ROLE_PANEL` or `ROLE_GROUPING`. And while treating a grouping like a panel makes sense, treating a section like a panel/grouping in Orca does not. (The little voice in the back of my mind is whispering that as soon as someone notices that "generic" = "section" and makes that change, accessibility is going to break.)

Getting back to the problem at hand.... Looking more at the Atspi roles, I can see why "grouping" made/makes sense:
* [`ROLE_GROUPING`](https://docs.gtk.org/atspi2/enum.Role.html#grouping): "A group of related widgets. This group typically has a label."
* [`ROLE_PANEL`](https://docs.gtk.org/atspi2/enum.Role.html#panel): "A generic container that is often used to group objects."

We're just suffering from the fact that no grouping has shown up until now, and panels with labels and presentable text are pretty common.

Again, I can see about backporting my changes to Orca 47 if you feel that is the most logical direction to go in. Lemme know what you think. And thanks!

note.body:
I see the "panel" role for GTK4 apps, so maybe there are some things which are mapped to that by default, like maybe GtkBox? Dunno....

BTW, WAI-ARIA dictates what web authors do. The Core-AAM dictates how that ARIA authoring should be exposed to assistive technologies. For instance ARIA has a ["group" role](https://w3c.github.io/aria/#group) that web authors can use. Chromium, WebKit, and Gecko developers look [here in the Core-AAM](https://w3c.github.io/core-aam/#role-map-group) to see how it should be exposed. For ATK/AT-SPI2, the table says `ROLE_PANEL` and that's what Orca gets (assuming spec-compliant implementations).

If you search the Core-AAM for "ROLE_PANEL", you'll find it's used for the following ARIA roles:

* feed
* group
* radiogroup
* rowgroup
 
If you search instead for "ROLE_GROUPING", you'll find it's not used.

All of this said, it's not wrong for you to use the grouping role. It's just that no toolkit or web engine had being doing so and Orca has never ever had special handling for it. In the case of panels, Orca looks for static text to present.

And happily Orca v48 has support for the "grouping" role. So if I can cleanly backport the relevant bits, cool. (The grouping support in some places touches code that doesn't exist in Orca v47.)

Orca would be happy with the window if that makes actually sense in Qt. This matters because Orca also cares about consistency in parent-child relations. In other words, if `foo` claims that its parent is `bar`, `bar` better claim `foo` as one of its children.  And if that for some reason doesn't make sense in Qt, we may just be asking for future breakage.

If there's no window that makes sense as the parent of the menu, maybe try setting the parent to the application (and ensure the application claims the menu as a child)? If that is the approach taken, I may need to make a corresponding change in Orca. But I won't know that until I have more information.

I know that my answers here are rather vague, but do you think you have enough to go on to tackle a fix in Qt or the app and get back to me with your findings? If not, let me know. Thanks!

note.body:
I'm afraid I cannot change sessions right now. That said, looking at your debug.out when we process the event, I see:

```
14:50:39.345018 - AXObject: [popup menu] has index -1 ; parent [application: 'kwin'] has 2 children
14:50:39.345050 - SCRIPT UTILITIES: None is top-level object for: [menu item: 'Auf Arbeitsfläche verschieben']
14:50:39.345056 - QT: Ignoring event because we couldn't find an ancestor window.
```

* Having an index in parent of -1 suggests something is broken.
* Not being able to ascend the accessibility tree is also bad.

So, yeah, an event is being fired. But it's coming from a subtree with problems and Orca is bailing.

What would be great is the following:

1. Modify your event listener so that it prints each parent of the newly-focused object. My guess is that this will fail at some point, just like it is for Orca.
2. File a bug against Qt so that they fix this bug, though see if it's this bug first: https://bugreports.qt.io/browse/QTBUG-129656

note.body:
So I just tried to reproduce this using the same version of Dolphin and the only bad thing I noticed is that when up/down arrowing Orca spoke the full line rather than the selected icon, which is not what you're reporting here. But I'll look into that next. 

In the meantime, your debug.out suggests that what Orca is doing is response to what Dolphin is doing. In particular:

1. The "kdf" list item claims focus. It has the following description ", Ordner, Größe: 10 Elemente". Description presentation is enabled by default. Thus Orca presents the name and description.
2. The list containing "kdf" fires a description change event. The list now has the description of "kdf,   , Ordner, Größe: 10 Elemente  in a grid layout in location file:///home/chrys/Build". Something that changed in Orca v47 is that Orca now presents description-changes on ancestors of focus. This allows for the automatic presentation of static text. So I'll add some filtering for this scenario, but would you happen to know why Dolphin is updating the list description to include the focused item? That's just asking for double presentation....

target_title: Orca does not read Unicode Braille Patterns on Ubuntu 22.04 LTS

note.body:
Looking at my debug.out from a supported version of Orca, Orca is sending the unicode braille symbol to speech-dispatcher. What happens (or fails to happen) is up to either speech-dispatcher or the synthesizer.

Based on my tests it appears that it's the synthesizer rather than speech-dispatcher that is handling this. More specifically, Orca presented the symbols for every synthesizer I tried with the exception of Voxin.

It could be that the reporter is not using a synthesizer (or version thereof) which supports the braille symbols. Another possibility is, as Andre stated, using a super old version of Orca. A few versions ago, Orca turned over all character presentation over to speech-dispatcher and the synthesizers. Before that, there were character presentation bugs and inconsistencies.
